inflammatory cells that accumulate in the lungs during chronic heart failure and are detected using Prussian blue staining?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Kupffer cells","Siderophages","Red pulp macrophages","Langerhans cells","Foam cells"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Esiderophages\u003C/strong\u003E. They are commonly seen in the lungs of patients with chronic heart failure, where pulmonary congestion leads to red blood cell extravasation into the alveoli. Siderophages are iron-laden macrophages that are a result of macrophages that phagocytose the red blood cells, and their degradation releases hemosiderin, an iron-storage complex.  They can be detected using Prussian blue staining and their presences indicates chronic pulmonary congestion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKupffer cells\u003C/strong\u003E are specialised macrophages located in the liver sinusoids and are not typically associated with heart failure or detected by Prussian blue staining.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERed pulp macrophages\u003C/strong\u003E are found in the spleen and are not specifically related to heart failure or Prussian blue staining.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELangerhans cells\u003C/strong\u003E are dendritic cells found in the skin and mucous membranes, and are not associated with heart failure or Prussian blue staining.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFoam cells\u003C/strong\u003E are lipid-laden macrophages commonly associated with atherosclerosis and are not specifically detected by Prussian blue staining or related to pulmonary congestion in heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Siderophages are iron-laden macrophages detected in heart failure using Prussian blue staining.","Siderophages indicate chronic pulmonary congestion and haemosiderin deposition in heart failure."],"references":["Ghio AJ, Roggli VL. Perls\u0027 Prussian Blue Stains of Lung Tissue, Bronchoalveolar Lavage, and Sputum. J Environ Pathol Toxicol Oncol. 2021;40(1):1-15. doi: 10.1615/JEnvironPatholToxicolOncol.2020036292. PMID: 33639069; PMCID: PMC8981511.","Goldblum, J. R., Zander, D. S., \u0026 Farver, C. F. Pulmonary Pathology: A Volume in the Series Foundations in Diagnostic Pathology. 2018. Elsevier."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98024"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14423"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98024"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T11:33:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T11:33:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7118"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116028"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}